title: 3 Body Problem (S1E2) | Copernicus's Encounter with the Count and the Follower
description:
In this pivotal scene from Three-Body Problem Season 1, Episode 2, physicist Jin Cheng (portrayed by Jess Hong) dons the VR headset provided by Ye Wenjie, entering the virtual realm of "Three-Body." Assuming the avatar of Copernicus, she meets the Count of the West and his companion, the Follower. The Count invites Copernicus to the pyramid to consult Emperor Zhou on the sun's erratic movements, explaining that during chaotic eras, the emperor seeks guidance from scholars to ensure the survival of their people. As they discuss, the virtual sun unexpectedly rises from the cold night, melting surrounding ice. Seeking shelter under a rock, space constraints force the Count to push the Follower out. The Follower pleads not to be abandoned, then removes her coat and lies on the ground. Under Copernicus's astonished gaze, she dehydrates under the sun's heat, leaving only her skin. When the sun sets, the Count rolls the dried skin and hands it to Copernicus, explaining that dehydration preserves individuals during chaotic eras, allowing rehydration in stable times. They then proceed toward the pyramid.​

Virtual Reality Immersion: Jin Cheng's experience as Copernicus offers a deep dive into the game's complex world.​

Civilization's Ritual: The depiction of dehydration as a survival mechanism during chaotic eras highlights the civilization's resilience.​

Sacrificial Act: The Follower's voluntary dehydration underscores themes of devotion and the lengths individuals go to ensure their community's survival.​

Complex World-Building: The series intricately weaves virtual reality with profound cultural practices, offering viewers a unique narrative experience.​

Stunning Visuals: The portrayal of the virtual sun and the dehydration process is both visually captivating and thought-provoking.​

Deep Philosophical Themes: The episode delves into survival, sacrifice, and the human spirit's resilience, prompting viewers to reflect on their own beliefs and values.​

The Rookie is an American police procedural television series created by Alexi Hawley for ABC. The series follows John Nolan, a man in his forties, who becomes the oldest rookie at the Los Angeles Police Department (LAPD). The series is produced by ABC Signature and Lionsgate Television; it is based on real-life LAPD officer William Norcross, who moved to Los Angeles in 2015 and joined the department in his mid-40s.

The series stars Nathan Fillion (John Nolan), Alyssa Diaz (Angela Lopez), Richard T.
